[1] India (Uttar Pradesh)
Date: Sat 11 Nov 2006
From: Joseph Dudley <jdudley@eaicorp.com>
Source: Adelaide now, Agence France Presse report [edited]
<http://www.news.com.au/adelaidenow/story/0,22606,20743176-5005962,00.html>

India (Uttar Pradesh): 25 new polio cases reported
-----------------------------------------------
25 new cases of polio in a week have been announced from the country's
north, one day ahead of the launch of an emergency vaccination drive for
120 million children. The new numbers take the regional tally to 438 and
were reported from the worst-hit Uttar Pradesh state, which has registered
more than a quarter of the world total. "Health officials will launch an
extensive door-to-door campaign to vaccinate 50 million children below 5
years of age in the state as polio virus has spread to new districts," A.K.
Mishra, the state's top health official, said.
The polio outbreak in Uttar Pradesh, the country's most populous state, has
raised fears that the disease could spread abroad from India if the
outbreak is not rapidly brought under control. The disease is caused by a
virus which affects the nervous system and is transmitted through feces. It
can paralyze a child for life within hours.
In a separate tally, the Global Polio Eradication Initiative, spearheaded
by the Geneva-based World Health Organization, put the nationwide number at
490 as of Wednesday [8 Nov 2006], more than 10 times the number of cases in
the same period last year [2005].
Federal health workers, along with the United Nations Children's Fund and
the World Health Organization, were due to vaccinate more than 120 million
children nationwide over 3 days beginning tomorrow [Sun 12 Nov 2006].
--
Joseph P. Dudley, Ph.D.
